def links_per_page(url):
    """
    Input string url link. 
    Returns a one item list of links to articles.
    """
    aggie_req = requests.get(url) #Ping the server
    aggie_html = aggie_req.text #Obtain the text file of the webstie
    aggie = BeautifulSoup(aggie_html, 'lxml') #Change to html code
    urls = [x.findNext().get('href') for x in aggie.findAll('h2')] #Use h2 to look for the article url. All articles across all pages are located in the h2 tab. Extracting this seciton will provide an easy approach to extracting the website urls. 
    return urls

def allLinks(pathway, num_page = 1):
    """
    Function arguements:
    string = complete url pathway
    int = number of pages of articles requested
    returns a list of urls for articles where each list item contains all urls on that page.
    """ 
    pages_requested = range(1, num_page + 1)
    link = [(pathway + 'page/' + str(x) + '/') for x in pages_requested]
    links = [links_per_page(x) for x in link]
    return(links)

def article_elements(article):
    """
    Input: String of complete url
    Output: Dictionary containing author, text, title, and url of article
    """
    aggie_req_art = requests.get(article) #Ping the server
    aggie_html_art = aggie_req_art.text #Obtain the text file of the webstie
    aggie_art = BeautifulSoup(aggie_html_art, 'lxml') #Change to html code

    adict = {'author':'','text':'','title':'','url':''} #Initialize the dictionary

    #Grab the title by looking for the class entry-title. Text in entry-title is the title of the article.      
    adict['title'] = aggie_art.find_all('h1',attrs={'class':'entry-title'})[0].get_text().encode('ascii', 'ignore')
 
    #The url is the one given in the function. Therefore, can append to the dictionary
    adict['url'] = article.encode('ascii', 'ignore')

    #Isolate the main body of the article. 
    body_text = aggie_art.find_all('div',attrs={'itemprop':'articleBody'})[0] #Itemprop named articleBody contains all of the writing found in the article excluding the title.
    paragraph = body_text.find_all('p') # Obtain a list of all of the paragraphs in the article. Contains text.

    #Obtain the text in the article
    #If FLICKR image is attached it grabs the subheading. Therefore, if statement checks to see if flickr is found in the text of the first paragraph. If so it takes out the portion before FLICKR, starting the article at the appropriate section.
    if (paragraph[0].getText().find("FLICKR") != -1) == True: 
        main_text_start = paragraph[0].getText().split("FLICKR")[1] + " "
    else:
        main_text_start = paragraph[0].getText() + " "
    main_text = main_text_start + " ".join([x.getText() for x in paragraph[1:-1]]) #Last item in list is author so take everything but the last element and join in a string. 
    adict['text'] = main_text.encode('ascii', 'ignore') #Change unicode numeric values to actual values.

    #Obtain the author of the article
    author_section = paragraph[len(paragraph)-1].getText() #Author is the last item in the main body list
    try:
        author_search = re.search("Written [Bb]y: [A-z]{1,20} [A-z]{2,20}", author_section)
        author_section = author_search.group(0)
        author = re.split("Written [Bb]y: ", author_section, flags=re.IGNORECASE)[-1] #Author has different html forms so finding written by will always grab the author. 
        adict['author'] = author.encode('ascii', 'ignore')
    except:
        adict['author'] = "NA"
    return adict

#Lecture Functions
stemmer = PorterStemmer().stem
tokenize = nltk.word_tokenize

def stem(tokens,stemmer = PorterStemmer().stem):
    return [stemmer(w.lower()) for w in tokens] 

def lemmatize(text):
    """
    Extract simple lemmas based on tokenization and stemming
    Input: string
    Output: list of strings (lemmata)
    """
    return stem(tokenize(text))

def Word_Counter(col_name, stops_to_add = {}):
    """
    Input: text in string or unicode from, set of words to be excluded from the counting process.
    Output: Counter class with number of occurences of each word in the string.
    """
    tokenizer = RegexpTokenizer(r'\w+')
    
    #Expand stopwords to only include words of interest. I only included filler words that would not add anything to my analysis.
    stopwords = set(STOPWORDS).union(stops_to_add)
    
    #Obtain a list of "important" words
    real_words = [word for word in tokenizer.tokenize(col_name) if word not in stopwords]
    
    #Find the lemmas corresponding to the words of interest.
    lemmatize_real_words = [lemmatize(x) for x in real_words]
    lemmata = [item for sublist in lemmatize_real_words for item in sublist]
    
    return Counter(lemmata)

The bar graphs above examine the counts of the top 20 most prevelant lemmas with the first graph only using the predetermined stopwords and the second graph using my additional stopwords. While it appears that some of my lemma are stop words, like "the" and "i", these are words that have been reduced down through lemmatization and therefore do not get captured by the stopwords. Examining the graphs it becomes apparent that there are specifc words that occur significantly more frequently than others. In the base stopword graph there are 5 count above 400 and no other values above 300. These five lemmas are "davi", "said", "student", "the", and "uc". It makes sense that Davi is high due to the Aggie covering UC Davis. The same llogic is true of UC and student. Said and the are externalities since these do not provide much useful information about the topic being covered. Examining past these 5 words there are similar topics related to community and students, reinforcing the wordclouds acquired above.

Examining the graph with the additional stopwords there is a bigger discrepancy between the top words and the rest of around 200-300 count. The stopwords added included words such as UC, Davis, said, and words that related more to geographic location or article type, like police log. Using this type of filtering I found that a large amount of the articles related to student activities, events, community news, university news, and state news. This makes sense since the Aggie as a Campus run newsaper would tend to cover more local events than national events as the readerbase would turn to larger news outlet for national news.

def sort_coo(m):
    """
    Input: tuple
    Output: tuple sorted.
    """
    tuples = izip(m.row, m.col, m.data)
    return sorted(tuples, key=lambda x: (x[0], x[2]), reverse = True)

#Figure out which three articles are the most closely related.
y = sim_matrix.tocoo()
ordered_sim = sort_coo(y) #Order the articles based on the articles first and the size second. Top value of each article now found every 120 values (number of columns in a row)
same_art = ordered_sim[0::120] #Since the articles are ordered in the way described above the top similiarty score for each article will occur every 120th value. Therefore extract these.
#Since there were articles along the diagonal that were not compared to itself, this means that an article was more similar to another article than itself. This is a potential concern that is addressed at the end of the seciton.

#Since don't care about articles compared to themselves find the articles that recieved the highest similiarty score excluding the same article. 
most_sim = []
for x in range(len(same_art)):
    if (same_art[x][0] != same_art[x][1]) == True: #Make sure that the original article does not match the comparison article
        most_sim.append(same_art[x])
        
top_three_sim = sorted(most_sim, key=lambda x: x[2], reverse = True)[0:3] #Find the top 3 values after acquring the sorted list with no comparisons to itself.

# 3 Pairs most closely related articles
print "The top 3 most related article pairs are: "
print "Group 1: "+articles_df["title"][top_three_sim[0][0]],"+",articles_df["title"][top_three_sim[0][1]]
print "Group 2: "+articles_df["title"][top_three_sim[1][0]],"+",articles_df["title"][top_three_sim[1][1]]
print "Group 3: "+articles_df["title"][top_three_sim[2][0]],"+",articles_df["title"][top_three_sim[2][1]]

The top 3 most related article pairs are: 
Group 1: 2017 ASUCD Winter Elections  Meet the Candidates + Drawing the lines of community ideals
Group 2: Construction of the All Student Center at Davis High begins + 2017 ASUCD Winter Elections  Meet the Candidates
Group 3: Russell Boulevard intramural fields withdrawn from 2017-2027 Long Range Development Plan + Student regent recruitment for the 2018-2019 school year begins

While the article pairings seem like they could be similar there are some major concerns with this model. These concerns are due to the nature of determining similairty in a sparse matrix. In a sparse matrix the scores are determined by the amount of words that match across the two articles being compared. The problem arises when the similiarity score inflates due to one article being small compared to the other. In this situation the small article can use words that are repeated many times in the larger article, resulting in the larger article recieving a high similiarty score to the smaller article due to sheer length. This occurs to such an extent that in multiple cases an article was matched more closely to another article than itself. Consequently, I would recommend using a weighted measure in the future as having drastic legnths in article can result in dramatic skews and false interpretations of the data.

Despite the findings listed in the prior paragraph the article pairings seem to be relevant or cover similar material. For instance, in group 1 it would make sense that ASUCD elections would cover the community ideals since the senators and president would seek to match the ideals with their platform. For group 2 the same ASUCD elcetions should cover pressing topics like construction occuring on campus. For group 3, the events occruing on Russell Bouevard could have a direct impact on recruitment or could be twisted to promote UC Davis to incoming students.

def Word_present(col_name, stops_to_add = {}):
    """
    Input: text in string or unicode from, set of words to be excluded from the counting process.
    Output: Counter class with number of occurences of each word in the string.
    """
    tokenizer = RegexpTokenizer(r'\w+')
    
    #Expand stopwords to only include words of interest. I only included filler words that would not add anything to my analysis.
    stopwords = set(STOPWORDS).union(stops_to_add)
    
    #Obtain a list of "important" words
    real_words = [word for word in tokenizer.tokenize(col_name) if word not in stopwords]
    
    return real_words

def common_elements(list1, list2):
    """
    Input: 2 lists
    Output: list of all similar values
    """
    return [element for element in list1 if element in list2] 

def shared(first, second, stops_to_add = {}):
    """
    Input: two strings
    Output: All shared unique words
    """
    words_pair_1= Word_present(first, stops_to_add) #Acquire only the important words and don't care about counts
    unique_words_1 = np.unique(words_pair_1) #Want only the unique words so get rid of duplicates
    words_pair_2 = Word_present(second, stops_to_add) #Acquire only the important words and don't care about counts
    unique_words_2 = np.unique(words_pair_2) #Want only the unique words so get rid of duplicates
    return common_elements(unique_words_1,unique_words_2) #Join the two lists based on only common elements

Do you think this corpus is representative of the Aggie? Why or why not? What kinds of inference can this corpus support? Explain your reasoning.

I do not believe the corpus is representative of the Aggie. The 120 articles examined here only encompased two of the Aggie's sections. Sports, Science, and Opinions, for instance, would all be very different from eachother as well as campus and city news. Additionally, there are different authors for different sections of the Aggie and each author has a unique writing style. Therefore, examining only two sections to make inferences about the whole newspaper would be a poor way to represent the Aggie. On top of this major problem, I only had 120 articles within the data. Articles are dependent on current events and therefore fluctuate dramatically based on what is happening in the world, as well as public sentitment towards these events. A span of 120 articles over two sections is in actuality only a time length of 60 articles (60 for each section). 60 articles only covers the span of around a month and therefore does not capture a large time frame. Thus, there will be a large amount of variance on article types, authors, and news being reported. Consequently, this further supports that the corpus is a bad representation of the Aggies. To fix these major issues I would recommend examining all of the different sections in the Aggie and look at 120-240 articles in each of these sections. This would provide significantly more data to reduce the variance based on the small time period as well as provide a wider base of inference to comment on the Aggie as a whole. While this would be more technologically and tim consuming, the results would be more signficant to drawing inferences about the newspaper.

This corpus could only be used to make inferneces on the city and campus sections of the Aggie. This is because of the aforementioned problem of different authors, writing styles, and news being reported for the different secitons. Additionally, these inferences would only support the article for a short period of time for these two sections in the Aggie. One reason would be high writer turnover where new authors could cause dramatic fluctuations in writing styles or news being reported. Depending on when the writers are hired or graduate, these ifnerences could last weeks to months to potentiall even years. Another limiting factor for these inferences is the current events. An example of this problem was seen in the news scraped over the last month where UC Davis ASUCD elections as well as presidential election helped shape the stories being covered in both the campus and city sections of the news. Once these events pass in the next couple weeks the newspaper will move on to cover other events, which will shape their diction and similiarity of articles. Thus, overall the coprus is a poor representation of the Aggie due to a mutlitude of varying factors..
